01:32:32,088 --> 01:32:34,250
He's young, not terribly bright.

1251
01:32:34,799 --> 01:32:38,212
It's not surprising he wouldn't
know what a state he put you in.

1252
01:32:38,636 --> 01:32:40,172
Sir, he's telling the truth.

1253
01:32:40,972 --> 01:32:45,136
Well, let's say for the moment
this Blatch does exist.

1254
01:32:45,393 --> 01:32:50,012
You think he'd just fall to his knees
and cry, "Yes, I did it. I confess.

1255
01:32:50,231 --> 01:32:52,939
Oh, and by the way,
add a life term to my sentence.â€

1256
01:32:53,151 --> 01:32:55,939
With Tommy's testimony,
I can get a new trial.

1257
01:32:56,154 --> 01:32:58,612
That's assuming Blatch is even still there.

1258
01:32:58,823 --> 01:33:00,780
Chances are, he'd be released by now.

1259
01:33:00,992 --> 01:33:05,577
They'd have his last known address,
names of relatives. It's a chance, isn't it?

1260
01:33:07,916 --> 01:33:09,657
How can you be so obtuse?

1261
01:33:10,585 --> 01:33:11,825
What?

1262
01:33:13,088 --> 01:33:14,544
What did you call me?

1263
01:33:14,756 --> 01:33:16,497
Obtuse. Is it deliberate?

1264
01:33:16,841 --> 01:33:18,331
You're forgetting yourself.

1265
01:33:18,676 --> 01:33:21,634
The country club
will have his old timecards.

1266
01:33:21,846 --> 01:33:24,588
Records, W-2s with his name on them.

1267
01:33:24,808 --> 01:33:27,516
If you want to indulge this fantasy,
it's your business.

1268
01:33:27,685 --> 01:33:30,302
Don't make it mine.
This meeting is over.

1269
01:33:30,522 --> 01:33:33,105
Sir, if I got out, I'd never mention
what happens here.

1270
01:33:33,733 --> 01:33:36,691
I'd be as indictable as you
for laundering that money.

1271
01:33:37,737 --> 01:33:41,526
Don't ever mention money to me again,
you sorry son of a bitch!

1272
01:33:41,699 --> 01:33:43,360
Not in this office...

1273
01:33:43,576 --> 01:33:45,533
...not anywhere. Get in here, now!

1274
01:33:45,745 --> 01:33:48,453
I just wanted to put you at ease,
that's all.

1275
01:33:49,082 --> 01:33:51,198
- Solitary. A month.
- Yes, sir.

1276
01:33:51,376 --> 01:33:54,164
- What's the matter with you?
- Get him out of here.

1277
01:33:54,379 --> 01:33:57,917
This is my chance to get out!
It's my life! Don't you understand?!

1278
01:33:58,133 --> 01:34:00,215
Get him out!

1279
01:34:01,970 --> 01:34:03,927
A month in the hole.

1280
01:34:04,139 --> 01:34:06,847
That's the longest stretch
I ever heard of.

1281
01:34:07,058 --> 01:34:08,344
It's all my fault.

1282
01:34:08,560 --> 01:34:10,142
Oh, bullshit.

1283
01:34:10,812 --> 01:34:13,520
You didn't pull the trigger
or convict him.

1284
01:34:13,731 --> 01:34:16,098
Are you saying Andy is innocent?

1285
01:34:16,317 --> 01:34:18,354
I mean, for real innocent?

1286
01:34:18,570 --> 01:34:19,901
It looks that way.

1287
01:34:20,321 --> 01:34:22,232
Sweet Jesus.

1288
01:34:22,490 --> 01:34:24,322
How long has he been here now?

1289
01:34:24,742 --> 01:34:27,985
1947. What is that? Nineteen years.

1290
01:34:28,246 --> 01:34:30,829
- Williams, Thomas.
- Yeah, over here.

1291
01:34:36,671 --> 01:34:37,832
What you got?

1292
01:34:38,464 --> 01:34:39,795
Board of Education.

1293
01:34:40,008 --> 01:34:41,544
That son of a bitch mailed it.

1294
01:34:41,759 --> 01:34:45,718
You going to open it or stand there
with your thumb up your butt?

1295
01:34:45,930 --> 01:34:48,092
Thumb up my butt sounds better.

1296
01:34:48,600 --> 01:34:51,433
Hey, Skeet, come on.
Give me that, you shithead.

1297
01:34:52,270 --> 01:34:53,601
Floyd, come on.

1298
01:34:56,191 --> 01:34:57,932
Hey, Red.

1299
01:34:59,027 --> 01:35:01,439
Will you throw that away, please?

1300
01:35:07,035 --> 01:35:08,776
Well, shit.

1301
01:35:21,466 --> 01:35:24,254
The kid passed. C-plus average.

1302
01:35:24,469 --> 01:35:26,551
Thought you'd like to know.

1303
01:35:42,779 --> 01:35:44,235
Warden wants to talk.

1304
01:35:58,002 --> 01:35:59,037
Out here?

1305
01:35:59,254 --> 01:36:01,495
That's what the man said.

1306
01:36:17,605 --> 01:36:21,064
- Warden?
- Tommy?

1307
01:36:26,990 --> 01:36:32,702
Tommy, I'm asking you to keep
this conversation just between us.

1308
01:36:34,205 --> 01:36:36,446
I feel awkward enough as it is.

1309
01:36:54,892 --> 01:36:56,974
We got a situation here.

1310
01:36:57,854 --> 01:36:59,936
I think you can appreciate that.

1311
01:37:00,148 --> 01:37:01,388
Yes, sir.

1312
01:37:01,649 --> 01:37:03,060
I sure can.

1313
01:37:03,318 --> 01:37:07,357
I tell you, son, this thing really
came along and knocked my wind out.

1314
01:37:08,823 --> 01:37:11,406
It's got me up nights. That's the truth.

1315
01:37:13,661 --> 01:37:15,493
The right thing to do...

1316
01:37:17,165 --> 01:37:20,908
...sometimes it's hard to know
what that is.

1317
01:37:21,919 --> 01:37:23,330
Do you understand?

1318
01:37:25,631 --> 01:37:27,247
I need your help, son.

1319
01:37:28,676 --> 01:37:30,838
If I'm going to move on this...

1320
01:37:31,179 --> 01:37:34,342
...there can't be
the least little shred of doubt.

1321
01:37:35,099 --> 01:37:36,134
I have to know...

1322
01:37:36,309 --> 01:37:38,971
...if what you told Dufresne
was the truth.

1323
01:37:39,187 --> 01:37:40,302
Yes, sir.

1324
01:37:40,521 --> 01:37:41,761
Absolutely.

1325
01:37:42,273 --> 01:37:45,265
Would you be willing to swear
before a judge and jury...

1326
01:37:45,443 --> 01:37:47,434
...with your hand on the Good Book...

1327
01:37:47,653 --> 01:37:50,315
...and take an oath
before Almighty God himself?

1328
01:37:50,531 --> 01:37:52,317
Just give me that chance.

1329
01:37:56,621 --> 01:37:57,952
That's what I thought.

1330
01:38:45,002 --> 01:38:46,913
I'm sure by now you've heard.

1331
01:38:48,673 --> 01:38:49,708
Terrible thing.

1332
01:38:51,342 --> 01:38:52,798
A man that young...

1333
01:38:53,136 --> 01:38:55,719
...less than a year to go,
trying to escape.

1334
01:38:56,264 --> 01:38:58,756
Broke Captain Hadley's heart
to shoot him.

1335
01:38:59,517 --> 01:39:01,007
Truly, it did.

1336
01:39:04,021 --> 01:39:06,433
We just have to put it behind us.

1337
01:39:08,109 --> 01:39:09,349
Move on.

1338
01:39:10,945 --> 01:39:12,435
I'm done.

1339
01:39:13,739 --> 01:39:15,355
Everything stops.

1340
01:39:17,368 --> 01:39:19,700
Get someone else to run your scams.

1341
01:39:20,955 --> 01:39:22,787
Nothing stops.

1342
01:39:24,125 --> 01:39:25,490
Nothing.

1343
01:39:28,713 --> 01:39:31,796
Or you will do the hardest time there is.

1344
01:39:32,216 --> 01:39:34,548
No more protection from the guards.

1345
01:39:34,719 --> 01:39:39,634
I'll pull you out of that one-bunk Hilton
and cast you down with the sodomites.

1346
01:39:41,058 --> 01:39:43,470
You'll think you've been
fucked by a train.

1347
01:39:44,896 --> 01:39:46,386
And the library?

1348
01:39:47,064 --> 01:39:48,054
Gone.

1349
01:39:48,649 --> 01:39:51,232
Sealed off, brick by brick.

1350
01:39:51,694 --> 01:39:54,356
We'll have us a little
book barbecue in the yard.

1351
01:39:54,572 --> 01:39:56,688
They'll see the flames for miles.

1352
01:39:56,908 --> 01:39:59,741
We'll dance around it like wild Injuns.

1353
01:40:00,995 --> 01:40:03,987
You understand me? Catching my drift?

1354
01:40:07,752 --> 01:40:09,584
Or am I being obtuse?

1355
01:40:21,390 --> 01:40:24,007
Give him another month
to think about it.

1356
01:41:10,773 --> 01:41:13,811
My wife used to say
I'm a hard man to know.

1357
01:41:14,652 --> 01:41:16,484
Like a closed book.

1358
01:41:17,280 --> 01:41:19,317
Complained about it all the time.

1359
01:41:20,241 --> 01:41:21,823
She was beautiful.

1360
01:41:24,203 --> 01:41:26,035
God, I loved her.

1361
01:41:29,458 --> 01:41:31,665
I didn't know how to show it, that's all.

1362
01:41:34,422 --> 01:41:36,083
I killed her, Red.

1363
01:41:37,967 --> 01:41:39,753
I didn't pull the trigger...

1364
01:41:41,178 --> 01:41:42,919
...but I drove her away.

1365
01:41:44,432 --> 01:41:47,140
That's why she died, because of me...

1366
01:41:47,310 --> 01:41:48,675
...the way I am.

1367
01:41:57,695 --> 01:41:59,527
That don't make you a murderer.

1368
01:42:02,908 --> 01:42:04,694
Bad husband, maybe.

1369
01:42:08,331 --> 01:42:11,574
Feel bad about it if you want,
but you didn't pull the trigger.

1370
01:42:11,792 --> 01:42:13,123
No, I didn't.

1371
01:42:13,544 --> 01:42:15,455
Somebody else did.

1372
01:42:16,714 --> 01:42:18,796
And I wound up in here.

1373
01:42:21,260 --> 01:42:22,876
Bad luck, I guess.

1374
01:42:25,765 --> 01:42:29,508
- Yeah.
- It floats around.

1375
01:42:30,561 --> 01:42:32,768
It's got to land on somebody.

1376
01:42:33,689 --> 01:42:35,555
It was my turn, that's all.

1377
01:42:36,275 --> 01:42:39,063
I was in the path of the tornado.

1378
01:42:44,992 --> 01:42:48,951
I just didn't expect the storm
would last as long as it has.

1379
01:42:53,292 --> 01:42:54,999
Think you'll ever get out of here?

1380
01:42:56,253 --> 01:42:57,664
Me?

1381
01:43:00,257 --> 01:43:01,588
Yeah.

1382
01:43:02,593 --> 01:43:04,880
One day, when I got
a long, white beard...

1383
01:43:05,096 --> 01:43:09,181
...and two or three marbles rolling
around upstairs, they'll let me out.

1384
01:43:10,267 --> 01:43:11,928
I tell you where I'd go.

1385
01:43:13,396 --> 01:43:15,103
Zihuatanejo.

1386
01:43:15,940 --> 01:43:17,101
Say what?

1387
01:43:17,441 --> 01:43:19,273
Zihuatanejo.

1388
01:43:20,194 --> 01:43:21,855
It's in Mexico.

1389
01:43:23,239 --> 01:43:25,355
A little place on the Pacific Ocean.

1390
01:43:26,492 --> 01:43:29,280
You know what the Mexicans say
about the Pacific?

1391
01:43:29,453 --> 01:43:33,117
- No.
- They say it has no memory.

1392
01:43:35,084 --> 01:43:37,746
That's where I want to live
the rest of my life.

1393
01:43:39,380 --> 01:43:41,872
A warm place with no memory.

1394
01:43:45,136 --> 01:43:47,047
Open up a little hotel...

1395
01:43:48,764 --> 01:43:50,254
...right on the beach.

1396
01:43:50,850 --> 01:43:53,057
Buy some worthless old boat...

1397
01:43:53,602 --> 01:43:55,218
...and fix it up new.

1398
01:43:57,982 --> 01:43:59,188
Take my guests out...

1399
01:44:00,025 --> 01:44:01,390
...Charter fishing.

1400
01:44:05,239 --> 01:44:06,980
Zihuatanejo.

1401
01:44:10,494 --> 01:44:14,362
In a place like that, I could use
a man that knows how to get things.

1402
01:44:20,921 --> 01:44:23,754
I don't think I could make it
on the outside, Andy.

1403
01:44:30,431 --> 01:44:32,513
I been in here most of my life.

1404
01:44:33,934 --> 01:44:35,675
I'm an institutional man now.

1405
01:44:36,604 --> 01:44:38,345
Just like Brooks was.

1406
01:44:38,981 --> 01:44:41,518
Well, you underestimate yourself.

1407
01:44:42,067 --> 01:44:43,683
I don't think so.

1408
01:44:47,531 --> 01:44:51,445
In here I'm the guy who can get things
for you, sure, but...

1409
01:44:52,203 --> 01:44:54,740
...outside all you need
is the Yellow Pages.

1410
01:44:54,955 --> 01:44:57,196
Hell, I wouldn't know
where to begin.

1411
01:44:59,335 --> 01:45:00,951
Pacific Ocean?

1412
01:45:01,378 --> 01:45:02,584
Shit.

1413
01:45:02,963 --> 01:45:05,170
Scare me to death, something that big.

1414
01:45:05,382 --> 01:45:06,668
Not me.

1415
01:45:07,885 --> 01:45:10,627
I didn't shoot my wife,
and I didn't shoot her lover.

1416
01:45:12,389 --> 01:45:15,598
Whatever mistakes I made,
I've paid for them and then some.

1417
01:45:16,644 --> 01:45:18,134
That hotel, that boat...

1418
01:45:19,897 --> 01:45:22,138
I don't think that's too much to ask.

1419
01:45:27,071 --> 01:45:29,483
You shouldn't be doing this to yourself.

1420
01:45:29,698 --> 01:45:31,735
This is just shitty pipe dreams.

1421
01:45:32,159 --> 01:45:34,617
Mexico is way down there
and you're in here...

1422
01:45:34,829 --> 01:45:36,411
...and that's the way it is.

1423
01:45:36,747 --> 01:45:39,580
Yeah, right. That's the way it is.

1424
01:45:41,085 --> 01:45:43,452
It's down there and I'm in here.

1425
01:45:46,048 --> 01:45:48,756
I guess it comes down
to a simple choice.

1426
01:45:51,679 --> 01:45:53,169
Get busy living...

1427
01:45:54,557 --> 01:45:56,594
...or get busy dying.

1428
01:46:00,229 --> 01:46:01,936
Andy.

1429
01:46:05,025 --> 01:46:06,686
Red?

1430
01:46:08,696 --> 01:46:11,438
If you ever get out of here,
do me a favor.

1431
01:46:11,615 --> 01:46:13,902
Sure, Andy. Anything.

1432
01:46:15,786 --> 01:46:19,620
There's a big hayfield up near Buxton.
You know where Buxton is?

1433
01:46:21,125 --> 01:46:24,243
- A lot of hayfields up there.
- One in particular.

1434
01:46:24,461 --> 01:46:28,375
It's got a long rock wall
with a big oak tree at the north end.

1435
01:46:28,591 --> 01:46:31,458
It's like something
out of a Robert Frost poem.

1436
01:46:32,386 --> 01:46:34,878
It's where I asked my wife to marry me.

1437
01:46:36,307 --> 01:46:38,389
We went there for a picnic...

1438
01:46:38,809 --> 01:46:40,891
...and made love under that oak...

1439
01:46:41,562 --> 01:46:43,803
...and I asked and she said yes.

1440
01:46:47,818 --> 01:46:49,650
Promise me, Red.

1441
01:46:50,487 --> 01:46:52,103
If you ever get out...

1442
01:46:52,323 --> 01:46:53,813
...find that spot.

1443
01:46:54,992 --> 01:46:59,828
At the base of that wall, there's a rock
that has no earthly business in Maine.

1444
01:47:00,956 --> 01:47:03,994
Piece of black, volcanic glass.

1445
01:47:06,670 --> 01:47:09,332
Something's buried under it
I want you to have.

1446
01:47:10,090 --> 01:47:11,330
What, Andy?

1447
01:47:11,759 --> 01:47:13,500
What's buried under there?

1448
01:47:15,095 --> 01:47:16,961
You'll have to pry it up...

1449
01:47:17,181 --> 01:47:18,421
...To see.

1450
01:47:24,438 --> 01:47:26,270
No, I'm telling you. The guy is...

1451
01:47:26,941 --> 01:47:28,682
He's talking funny.

1452
01:47:29,777 --> 01:47:31,484
I'm really worried about him.

1453
01:47:31,862 --> 01:47:33,318
Let's keep an eye on him.

1454
01:47:33,530 --> 01:47:36,773
That's fine during the day,
but at night he's all alone.

1455
01:47:38,202 --> 01:47:39,363
Oh, Lord.

1456
01:47:40,704 --> 01:47:42,286
What?

1457
01:47:43,040 --> 01:47:45,782
Andy come down
to the loading dock today.

1458
01:47:46,001 --> 01:47:48,083
He asked me for a length of rope.

1459
01:47:48,295 --> 01:47:51,003
- Rope?
- Six feet long.

1460
01:47:51,215 --> 01:47:52,580
And you gave it to him.

1461
01:47:53,467 --> 01:47:55,253
Sure I did. Why wouldn't I?

1462
01:47:55,469 --> 01:47:57,051
Jesus! Heywood.

1463
01:47:57,638 --> 01:47:59,595
How was I supposed to know?

1464
01:47:59,807 --> 01:48:01,389
Remember Brooks Hatlen?

1465
01:48:01,600 --> 01:48:05,309
No. Andy would never do that.

1466
01:48:05,896 --> 01:48:07,352
Never.

1467
01:48:09,066 --> 01:48:10,397
I don't know.

1468
01:48:13,237 --> 01:48:15,228
Every man has his breaking point.

1469
01:48:17,574 --> 01:48:19,861
Lickety-split. Want to get home.

1470
01:48:20,160 --> 01:48:21,901
Just about finished, sir.

1471
01:48:39,054 --> 01:48:40,670
Three deposits tonight.

1472
01:48:48,647 --> 01:48:50,558
Get my stuff down to the laundry.

1473
01:48:50,774 --> 01:48:52,390
And shine my shoes.

1474
01:48:52,609 --> 01:48:55,522
- I want them looking like mirrors.
- Yes, sir.

1475
01:49:01,035 --> 01:49:02,491
It's good having you back, Andy.

1476
01:49:03,454 --> 01:49:05,286
Place wasn't the same without you.

1477
01:49:52,169 --> 01:49:53,534
Lights out!

1478
01:50:26,078 --> 01:50:28,615
I've had some long nights in the stir.

1479
01:50:29,164 --> 01:50:31,826
Alone in the dark
with nothing but your thoughts...

1480
01:50:32,042 --> 01:50:34,704
...time can draw out like a blade.

1481
01:50:40,050 --> 01:50:43,042
That was the longest night of my life.

1482
01:50:58,902 --> 01:51:00,063
Give me a count!

1483
01:51:04,575 --> 01:51:07,408
Tier 3 south, clear!

1484
01:51:10,539 --> 01:51:13,702
Man missing on tier 2, cell 245!

1485
01:51:13,917 --> 01:51:14,952
Dufresne!

1486
01:51:15,502 --> 01:51:17,914
Come out. You're holding up the show!

1487
01:51:21,091 --> 01:51:24,459
Don't make me come down
or I'll thump your skull for you!

1488
01:51:32,060 --> 01:51:35,894
Damn it, you're putting me behind!
I got a schedule to keep.

1489
01:51:36,106 --> 01:51:39,394
You'd better be sick or dead in there.
I shit you not!

1490
01:51:39,610 --> 01:51:40,941
You hear me?

1491
01:51:47,034 --> 01:51:49,116
Oh, my Holy God.

1492
01:52:06,136 --> 01:52:08,673
I want every man
on this cellblock questioned.

1493
01:52:09,139 --> 01:52:11,676
- Start with that friend of his.
- Who?

1494
01:52:11,850 --> 01:52:13,261
Him.

1495
01:52:14,269 --> 01:52:15,805
Open 237.

1496
01:52:19,316 --> 01:52:22,980
What do you mean, "He just wasn't here"?
Don't say that to me.

1497
01:52:23,862 --> 01:52:26,445
- Don't say that to me again.
- But, sir, he wasn't.

1498
01:52:26,657 --> 01:52:30,150
I can see that, Haig! Think I'm blind?

1499
01:52:30,827 --> 01:52:32,409
Is that what you're saying?

1500
01:52:32,579 --> 01:52:35,071
- Am I blind, Haig?
- No, sir!

1501
01:52:35,999 --> 01:52:38,491
What about you. You blind?

1502
01:52:39,002 --> 01:52:41,334
- Tell me what this is.
- Last night's count.

1503
01:52:41,505 --> 01:52:45,043
Uh-huh. You see Dufresne's name there?
I sure do. Right there.

1504
01:52:45,259 --> 01:52:46,590
"Dufresne."

1505
01:52:48,262 --> 01:52:51,004
He was in his cell at lights out.

1506
01:52:51,181 --> 01:52:54,094
Stands to reason he'd still be here
in the morning.

1507
01:52:54,434 --> 01:52:56,050
I want him found.

1508
01:52:56,270 --> 01:52:59,729
Not tomorrow, not after breakfast. Now!

1509
01:52:59,982 --> 01:53:01,188
Yes, sir.

1510
01:53:02,192 --> 01:53:05,981
Let's go. Move your butts. Move it!

1511
01:53:07,864 --> 01:53:08,854
Stand.

1512
01:53:10,284 --> 01:53:11,695
Well?

1513
01:53:14,788 --> 01:53:15,823
Well, what?

1514
01:53:15,998 --> 01:53:19,457
I see you two all the time.
You're thick as thieves, you are.

1515
01:53:20,544 --> 01:53:22,034
He must have said something.

1516
01:53:22,754 --> 01:53:25,667
No, sir, warden. Not a word.

1517
01:53:27,467 --> 01:53:30,050
Lord, it's a miracle!

1518
01:53:30,637 --> 01:53:33,220
Man vanished like a fart in the wind.

1519
01:53:33,890 --> 01:53:35,051
Nothing left...

1520
01:53:35,892 --> 01:53:38,600
...but some damn rocks
on a windowsill.

1521
01:53:38,812 --> 01:53:41,554
And that cupcake on the wall.
Let's ask her.

1522
01:53:41,732 --> 01:53:43,063
Maybe she knows.

1523
01:53:43,233 --> 01:53:46,442
What say there, fuzzy-britches?
Feel like talking?

1524
01:53:46,778 --> 01:53:49,236
Oh, guess not.

1525
01:53:49,781 --> 01:53:51,988
Why should she be any different?

1526
01:53:53,076 --> 01:53:54,737
This is a conspiracy.

1527
01:53:55,370 --> 01:53:57,077
That's what this is.

1528
01:53:57,789 --> 01:54:01,532
One big, damn conspiracy!

1529
01:54:01,793 --> 01:54:03,784
And everyone's in on it!

1530
01:54:04,421 --> 01:54:05,582
Including her!

1531
01:54:40,624 --> 01:54:42,331
In 1966...

1532
01:54:42,542 --> 01:54:44,954
...Andy Dufresne escaped...

1533
01:54:45,128 --> 01:54:46,710
...from Shawshank Prison.

1534
01:54:48,965 --> 01:54:51,502
All they found of him
was a muddy set of prison clothes...

1535
01:54:52,135 --> 01:54:53,671
...a bar of soap...

1536
01:54:53,887 --> 01:54:55,469
...and an old rock hammer...

1537
01:54:55,639 --> 01:54:58,131
...damn near worn down to the nub.

1538
01:55:02,646 --> 01:55:07,391
I remember thinking it would take a man
600 years to tunnel through the wall with it.

1539
01:55:08,026 --> 01:55:10,643
Old Andy did it in less than 20.

1540
01:55:28,964 --> 01:55:31,251
Oh, Andy loved geology.

1541
01:55:32,008 --> 01:55:35,171
I imagine it appealed to
his meticulous nature.

1542
01:55:35,595 --> 01:55:37,427
An ice age here...

1543
01:55:37,848 --> 01:55:40,340
...million years
of mountain-building there.

1544
01:55:41,351 --> 01:55:44,184
Geology is the study
of pressure and time.

1545
01:55:45,021 --> 01:55:47,012
That's all it takes, really.

1546
01:55:47,774 --> 01:55:49,060
Pressure...

1547
01:55:49,526 --> 01:55:51,016
...and time.

1548
01:55:52,112 --> 01:55:54,194
That and a big goddamn poster.

1549
01:55:57,993 --> 01:55:59,154
Like I said...

1550
01:55:59,661 --> 01:56:03,655
...in prison, a man will do anything
to keep his mind occupied.

1551
01:56:06,460 --> 01:56:11,250
Seems Andy's favorite hobby was toting
his wall out into the exercise yard...

1552
01:56:11,798 --> 01:56:13,709
...a handful at a time.

1553
01:56:15,051 --> 01:56:17,088
I guess after Tommy was Killed...

1554
01:56:17,304 --> 01:56:20,262
...Andy decided
he'd been here just about long enough.

1555
01:56:20,474 --> 01:56:23,057
Lickety-split. Want to get home.

1556
01:56:23,768 --> 01:56:25,805
I'm just about finished, sir.

1557
01:56:47,250 --> 01:56:49,207
Three deposits tonight.

1558
01:56:56,510 --> 01:56:58,797
Andy did like he was told.

1559
01:56:59,012 --> 01:57:02,505
Buffed those shoes
to a high mirror-shine.

1560
01:57:06,186 --> 01:57:08,473
The guards simply didn't notice.

1561
01:57:08,772 --> 01:57:10,262
Neither did I.

1562
01:57:10,440 --> 01:57:11,976
I mean, seriously...

1563
01:57:12,192 --> 01:57:15,184
...how often do you really look
at a man's shoes?

1564
01:59:18,735 --> 01:59:21,898
Andy crawled to freedom
through 500 yards...

1565
01:59:22,155 --> 01:59:25,489
...of shit-smelling foulness
I can't even imagine.

1566
01:59:26,493 --> 01:59:28,825
Or maybe I just don't want to.

1567
01:59:33,249 --> 01:59:35,581
Five hundred yards.

1568
01:59:36,086 --> 01:59:39,169
That's the length
of five football fields.

1569
01:59:39,798 --> 01:59:42,381
Just shy of half a mile.

1570
02:00:37,605 --> 02:00:42,190
The next morning, right about the time
Raquel was spilling her little secret...

1571
02:00:42,485 --> 02:00:45,318
...a man nobody ever
laid eyes on before...

1572
02:00:45,572 --> 02:00:48,155
...strolled into
the Maine National Bank.

1573
02:00:48,742 --> 02:00:51,905
Until that moment, he didn't exist.

1574
02:00:52,495 --> 02:00:54,827
- Except on paper.
- May I help you?

1575
02:00:55,248 --> 02:00:57,159
He had all the proper ID--

1576
02:00:57,375 --> 02:01:01,084
Driver's license, birth certificate,
Social Security card.

1577
02:01:01,504 --> 02:01:04,041
--And the signature
was a spot-on match.

1578
02:01:04,257 --> 02:01:07,340
I must say I'm sorry
to be losing your business.

1579
02:01:07,552 --> 02:01:09,293
I hope you'll enjoy living abroad.

1580
02:01:10,096 --> 02:01:11,678
Thank you.

1581
02:01:11,848 --> 02:01:13,009
I'm sure I will.

1582
02:01:13,933 --> 02:01:17,267
Here's your cashier's check, sir.
Will there be anything else?

1583
02:01:17,479 --> 02:01:18,469
Please.

1584
02:01:19,022 --> 02:01:21,514
Would you add this
to your outgoing mail?

1585
02:01:22,025 --> 02:01:23,561
I'd be happy to.

1586
02:01:25,028 --> 02:01:26,359
Good day, sir.

1587
02:01:27,322 --> 02:01:31,737
Mr. Stevens visited nearly
a dozen banks in the Portland area.

1588
02:01:32,202 --> 02:01:33,818
All told, he blew town...

1589
02:01:34,037 --> 02:01:38,873
...with better than $370,000
of Warden Norton's money.

1590
02:01:39,542 --> 02:01:42,330
Severance pay for 19 years.

1591
02:01:49,552 --> 02:01:51,759
Good morning, Portland Daily Bugle.

1592
02:02:44,607 --> 02:02:47,565
Byron Hadley?
You have the right to remain silent.

1593
02:02:47,819 --> 02:02:52,279
If you give up this right, anything you
say can be held against you in court.

1594
02:02:52,699 --> 02:02:57,159
I wasn't there to see it, but I hear
Byron Hadley sobbed like a little girl...

1595
02:02:57,370 --> 02:02:58,860
...when they took him away.

1596
02:03:04,752 --> 02:03:08,120
Norton had no intention
of going that quietly.

1597
02:03:24,105 --> 02:03:25,470
Samuel Norton.

1598
02:03:25,648 --> 02:03:27,639
We have a warrant for your arrest.
Open up.

1599
02:03:31,279 --> 02:03:34,271
Norton. Open the door.

1600
02:03:34,449 --> 02:03:35,689
I'm not sure which key.

1601
02:03:38,494 --> 02:03:40,405
Norton!

1602
02:03:45,835 --> 02:03:47,792
Make it easy on yourself, Norton!

1603
02:03:59,307 --> 02:04:02,766
I like to think the last thing
that went through his head...

1604
02:04:02,977 --> 02:04:04,559
...other than that bullet...

1605
02:04:04,771 --> 02:04:09,186
...was to wonder how the hell
Andy Dufresne ever got the best of him.

1606
02:04:11,694 --> 02:04:15,187
Not long after the warden
deprived us of his company...

1607
02:04:15,448 --> 02:04:17,530
<i>...1 got a postcard in the mail.</i>

1608
02:04:18,993 --> 02:04:21,826
It was blank, but the postmark said...

1609
02:04:22,038 --> 02:04:24,154
...Fort Hancock, Texas.

1610
02:04:24,707 --> 02:04:26,038
Fort Hancock...

1611
02:04:26,334 --> 02:04:28,041
...right on the border.

1612
02:04:28,461 --> 02:04:30,452
That's where Andy crossed.

1613
02:04:31,047 --> 02:04:35,166
When I picture him heading south
in his own car with the top down...

1614
02:04:35,510 --> 02:04:37,717
...It always makes me laugh.

1615
02:04:39,555 --> 02:04:41,137
Andy Dufresne...

1616
02:04:41,516 --> 02:04:43,553
...who crawled through
a river of shit...

1617
02:04:43,726 --> 02:04:46,138
...and came out clean
on the other side.

1618
02:04:46,980 --> 02:04:48,345
Andy Dufresne...

1619
02:04:49,148 --> 02:04:50,730
...headed for the Pacific.

1620
02:04:53,736 --> 02:04:55,898
Hadley's got him
by the throat, right?

1621
02:04:56,072 --> 02:04:59,906
He says, "I believe this boy's
about to have himself an accident.â€

1622
02:05:00,076 --> 02:05:02,943
Those of us who knew him best
talk about him often.

1623
02:05:03,621 --> 02:05:05,328
I swear, the stuff he pulled...

1624
02:05:05,540 --> 02:05:08,498
"My friends could use
a couple of beers."

1625
02:05:08,835 --> 02:05:10,496
And he got it!

1626
02:05:11,754 --> 02:05:14,121
Sometimes it makes me sad, though...

1627
02:05:14,424 --> 02:05:15,835
...Andy being gone.

1628
02:05:16,551 --> 02:05:20,670
I have to remind myself that
some birds aren't meant to be caged.

1629
02:05:21,139 --> 02:05:23,221
Their feathers are just too bright.

1630
02:05:24,934 --> 02:05:26,641
And when they fly away...

1631
02:05:27,103 --> 02:05:31,472
...the part of you that knows it was
a sin to lock them up does rejoice.

1632
02:05:32,567 --> 02:05:33,807
But still...

1633
02:05:34,277 --> 02:05:38,612
...the place you live in is that much
more drab and empty that they're gone.

1634
02:05:42,827 --> 02:05:45,194
I guess I just miss my friend.

1635
02:06:09,645 --> 02:06:10,806
Please sit down.

1636
02:06:16,652 --> 02:06:18,234
Ellis Boyd Redding...

1637
02:06:18,780 --> 02:06:22,023
...your files say you've served
40 years of a life sentence.

1638
02:06:22,825 --> 02:06:24,987
You feel you've been rehabilitated?

1639
02:06:26,829 --> 02:06:28,411
Rehabilitated?

1640
02:06:30,458 --> 02:06:32,324
Well, now, let me see.

1641
02:06:33,336 --> 02:06:35,668
I don't have any idea what that means.

1642
02:06:37,799 --> 02:06:40,040
It means you're ready
to rejoin society--

1643
02:06:40,635 --> 02:06:42,967
I know what you think it means, sonny.

1644
02:06:45,139 --> 02:06:47,130
To me it's just a made-up word.

1645
02:06:48,476 --> 02:06:50,808
A politician's word so that...

1646
02:06:51,229 --> 02:06:54,767
...young fellas like yourself
can wear a suit and a tie...

1647
02:06:55,233 --> 02:06:56,849
...and have a job.

1648
02:06:58,820 --> 02:07:00,902
What do you really want to know?

1649
02:07:01,697 --> 02:07:03,654
Am I sorry for what I did?

1650
02:07:04,075 --> 02:07:05,361
Well, are you?

1651
02:07:07,161 --> 02:07:09,994
There's not a day goes by
I don't feel regret.

1652
02:07:11,374 --> 02:07:14,833
Not because I'm in here
or because you think I should.

1653
02:07:18,297 --> 02:07:20,880
I look back on the way I was then...

1654
02:07:23,010 --> 02:07:24,341
...a young...

1655
02:07:25,263 --> 02:07:28,756
...stupid kid who committed
that terrible crime.

1656
02:07:31,769 --> 02:07:33,476
I want to talk to him.

1657
02:07:35,398 --> 02:07:37,890
I want to try
and talk some sense to him.

1658
02:07:38,609 --> 02:07:40,566
Tell him the way things are.

1659
02:07:42,655 --> 02:07:44,066
But I can't.

1660
02:07:46,284 --> 02:07:48,275
That kid's long gone...

1661
02:07:49,495 --> 02:07:52,237
...and this old man is all that's left.

1662
02:07:53,666 --> 02:07:55,122
I got to live with that.

1663
02:07:56,502 --> 02:07:58,209
Rehabilitated?

1664
02:07:58,588 --> 02:08:00,420
It's just a bullshit word.

1665
02:08:01,340 --> 02:08:06,085
So you go on and stamp your forms,
sonny, and stop wasting my time.

1666
02:08:07,346 --> 02:08:09,587
Because to tell you the truth...

1667
02:08:09,932 --> 02:08:11,923
...don't give a shit.

1668
02:09:38,479 --> 02:09:39,844
Here you go, miss.

1669
02:09:42,817 --> 02:09:43,852
Restroom break, boss?

1670
02:09:49,657 --> 02:09:54,197
You don't need to ask me every time you
need to go take a piss. Just go. Understand?

1671
02:09:55,204 --> 02:09:56,820
Yes, sir.

1672
02:10:07,216 --> 02:10:10,299
Forty years I've been asking
permission to piss.

1673
02:10:11,137 --> 02:10:14,129
I can't squeeze a drop without say-so.

1674
02:10:17,643 --> 02:10:19,805
There's a harsh truth to face.

1675
02:10:21,480 --> 02:10:24,393
No way I'm going to make it
on the outside.

1676
02:10:32,241 --> 02:10:35,950
All I do anymore is think of ways
to break my parole...

1677
02:10:36,746 --> 02:10:39,238
...So maybe they'd send me back.

1678
02:10:44,420 --> 02:10:46,878
Terrible thing, to live in fear.

1679
02:10:47,757 --> 02:10:49,418
Brooks Hatlen knew it.

1680
02:10:49,633 --> 02:10:51,590
Knew it all too well.

1681
02:10:53,179 --> 02:10:56,592
All I want is to be back
where things make sense.

1682
02:10:57,016 --> 02:10:59,758
Where I won't have to be afraid
all the time.

1683
02:11:01,771 --> 02:11:04,103
Only one thing stops me.

1684
02:11:05,566 --> 02:11:07,933
A promise I made to Andy.

1685
02:11:28,464 --> 02:11:29,795
There it is.

1686
02:11:40,226 --> 02:11:41,887
Much obliged, sir.

1687
02:15:21,196 --> 02:15:22,482
Dear Red:

1688
02:15:22,698 --> 02:15:25,190
If you're reading this,
you've gotten out...

1689
02:15:25,367 --> 02:15:29,531
...and if you've come this far,
maybe you're willing to come a little further.

1690
02:15:29,705 --> 02:15:32,197
You remember the name
of the town, don't you?

1691
02:15:34,501 --> 02:15:35,991
Zihuatanejo.

1692
02:15:37,630 --> 02:15:41,214
I could use a good man
to help me get my project on wheels.

1693
02:15:41,717 --> 02:15:45,255
I'll keep an eye out for you,
and the chessboard ready.

1694
02:15:46,055 --> 02:15:47,466
Remember, Red...

1695
02:15:47,806 --> 02:15:49,888
...hope is a good thing...

1696
02:15:50,100 --> 02:15:52,091
...maybe the best of things.

1697
02:15:52,311 --> 02:15:54,473
And no good thing ever dies.

1698
02:15:55,022 --> 02:15:57,889
I will be hoping
that this letter finds you...

1699
02:15:58,067 --> 02:15:59,808
...and finds you well.

1700
02:16:00,319 --> 02:16:01,559
Your friend...

1701
02:16:01,737 --> 02:16:02,898
...Andy.

1702
02:16:36,772 --> 02:16:38,479
"Get busy living...

1703
02:16:38,691 --> 02:16:40,602
...or get busy dying."

1704
02:16:43,278 --> 02:16:45,440
That's goddamn right.

1705
02:16:50,703 --> 02:16:52,819
For the second time in my life...

1706
02:16:53,080 --> 02:16:55,617
...I'm guilty of committing a crime.

1707
02:16:56,709 --> 02:16:58,620
Parole violation.

1708
02:16:59,294 --> 02:17:02,958
Of course, I doubt they'll toss up
any roadblocks for that.

1709
02:17:03,632 --> 02:17:05,669
Not for an old crook like me.

1710
02:17:05,884 --> 02:17:07,921
Fort Hancock, Texas, please.

1711
02:17:11,598 --> 02:17:16,308
I find I'm so excited I can barely
sit still or hold a thought in my head.

1712
02:17:16,770 --> 02:17:20,104
I think it's the excitement
only a free man can feel.

1713
02:17:20,315 --> 02:17:22,807
A free man at the start
of a long journey...

1714
02:17:22,985 --> 02:17:25,602
...whose conclusion is uncertain.

1715
02:17:28,615 --> 02:17:31,277
I hope I can make it across the border.

1716
02:17:32,786 --> 02:17:35,824
I hope to see my friend
and shake his hand.

1717
02:17:37,666 --> 02:17:41,751
I hope the Pacific is as blue
as it has been in my dreams.

1718
02:17:43,589 --> 02:17:44,795
I hope.
